  <div class="timeline-comment-wrapper js-comment-container">
    <a href="/micwallace"><img alt="@micwallace" class="timeline-comment-avatar" height="48" src="https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/3140819?v=3&amp;s=96" width="48" /></a>
    <div id="issue-36218298"
     class="comment previewable-edit timeline-comment js-comment js-task-list-container "
     data-body-version="5df0832d2c939df67e6b3d87a528680e">

  <div class="timeline-comment-header ">




  <div class="timeline-comment-header-text">

    <strong>
      <a href="/micwallace" class="author">micwallace</a>
    </strong>

    commented

    <a href="#issue-36218298" class="timestamp">
      <time datetime="2014-06-21T06:57:21Z" is="relative-time">Jun 21, 2014</time>
    </a>
  </div>
</div>


  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="comment-body markdown-body markdown-format js-comment-body">
          <p>I really like the your zxing app and wanted to suggest this. Happy to program the Android/Javascript part of it if people are interested.</p>

<p>A HTTP service mode for zxing.<br>
For better integration with websites.</p>

<p>Process:<br>
1. User visits webapp/webpage.<br>
2. App checks for xzing http sever.<br>
3. Is the server running? If not, prompt to install, or open using intent URL that triggers the service to start.<br>
4. zxing http server now running.<br>
5. User clicks on "scan barcode" button.<br>
6. Http requests are made every second to the zxing server url (ie http://localhost:8080).<br>
7. The server returns two things:<br>
    a. base64 encoded image of what the camera is seeing at that point<br>
    b. the captured barcode data (returned once for every barcode recognition).<br>
8. The javascript app show a small dialog to display the base64 image data and has a button to stop the barcode recognition.<br>
9. A callback is issued every time a barcode is received.</p>

<p>This would produce seamless integration for web-apps :-D</p>

<p>Please let me know what you think.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

  </div>
  


      


