    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="comment-body markdown-body email-format js-comment-body">
          <div class="email-fragment">Hi I've added functionality so it shuts down the http server when the
user navigates away from the http page. Also the server listens on
127.0.0.1 so only the device it's self can communicate with the server
plus the user needs to manually invoke the service each time it's used
(although the js automatically opens the android app for doing so). The
Camera can be accessed most places I think, I was quite surprised about
this as well.

That's all good, it's not a feature most would use.

Do you mind if I use your core decoding &amp; camera control classes/libs to
create a separate app to publish to the play store? It will just have
the HTTP Service feature included and probably be called something like
"Web Scanner" or, if you would like "Zxing Web Scanner".

Kind regards,
Michael</div>
<span class="email-hidden-toggle"><a href="#">…</a></span><div class="email-hidden-reply" style="display:none">
<div class="email-quoted-reply">On 23/06/14 16:29, Sean Owen wrote: &gt; OK. Does it not leave up a long-running HTTP server this way? and I am  &gt; not &gt; sure how it can use the camera in the background. I'm vaguely worried  &gt; this &gt; is a security/privacy hole. I didn't think this was possible for security &gt; reasons. I think this is an interesting modification although I think the &gt; changes are too substantial to push into the main project for everyone. &gt; &gt; &gt; On Sun, Jun 22, 2014 at 6:21 PM, micwallace &lt;notifications@github.com&gt; &gt; wrote: &gt; &gt; &gt; Hi Sean, &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; When using an web app it's not ideal to go back and forth between the &gt; &gt; app and the webpage, especially when scanning multiple barcodes. &gt; &gt; This basically provides access to the camera preview plus any decoded &gt; &gt; barcode text all from the web browser. &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Plus it wraps all the web functionality in a jquery widget, you can &gt; &gt; invoke the widget and issue js callbacks to fire when a barcode is &gt; &gt; found. I think you would be the first app to provide such a feature :-) &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Zxing is still doing all the handling of decoding and such. &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Give it a go and let me know what you think. &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Kind regards, &gt; &gt; Michael &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; On 23/06/14 02:53, Sean Owen wrote: &gt; &gt; &gt; OK. what's the advantage over launching the app, if you are  &gt; calling to &gt; &gt; &gt; something to retrieve frames and then sending them back for decoding? &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; On Sun, Jun 22, 2014 at 5:51 PM, micwallace  &gt; &lt;notifications@github.com&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; wrote:
